Plot before improvement

Source: https://www.reddit.com/r/theydidthemath/comments/11pb8c8/request_circles_were_used_instead_of_rectangles/

Plot after improvement

R code:

library(dplyr)
library(treemapify)
library(ggplot2)
df <- data.frame("bank_name" = c("Washington Mutual", "Silicon Valley", "Indy Mack", "Colonial", "Guaranty", "Downey Savings & Loan Association",
                                 "United", "Am Trust", "Westernbank Puerto Rico", "United Commercial"),
                 "assets" = c(307, 209, 32, 25, 13, 12.8, 12.8, 12, 11.94, 11.2),
                 "deposits" = c(188.3, 175.4, 18.9, 20.1, 12, 9.7, 7.5, 8, 8.62, 7.5))

df <- df %>% mutate(DAR = deposits / assets)
ggplot(df, aes(area = assets, fill = DAR, label = paste0(bank_name, "\n", paste0("$", assets, "bn")))) +
  geom_treemap() +
  geom_treemap_text(place = "centre", reflow = T, family = "serif", color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 banks failures since 2000",
       caption = "Values mean total assets of bank in the time of failure in billions of dollars", 
       fill = paste0("D/A.", "\n", "ratio")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 30, family = "serif", color = "gray15", face = "bold"),
        plot.caption = element_text(size = 12, family = "serif", color = "gray15", face = "bold"),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 15, family = "serif", color = "gray10", face = "bold"),
        legend.background = element_rect(colour = "gray15", linetype = "solid", size = 1),
        legend.key.size = unit(1, "cm"))

Justification

Reasons why new plot is actually better:

  • Initial plot had neither the title nor the legend, which led to confusion.

  • The plot with circles instead of rectangles has unreasonable amount of gaps.

  • There was too many data records used to plot, therefore most of them were not even traceable.

  • Treemap graph was chosen to remain the same visual effect. Because of the color mapping linked with this graph type, there was a need to add a new variable. D/A ratio estimates the range that assets are backed by part of the constant deposit. Higher the ratio indicates the chances of liquidity risk leading to bank failure.
